05136nam a22007695i 9780812291506DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122915067 a10.9783/97808122915062doi  a(DE-B1597)463539  a(OCoLC)979970126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a307.762221 aGordon, Colin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMapping Decline :bSt. Louis and the Fate of the American City /cColin Gordon. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b78 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Our House: The Twentieth Century at 4635 North Market Street -- t1. Local Politics, Local Power: Governing Greater St. Louis, 1940–2000 -- t2. ‘‘The Steel Ring’’: Race and Realty in Greater St. Louis -- t3. Patchwork Metropolis: Municipal Zoning in Greater St. Louis -- t4. Fighting Blight: Urban Renewal Policies and Programs, 1945–2188 -- t5. City of Blight: The Limits of Urban Renewal in Greater St. Louis -- tConclusion. Our House Revisited: The Twenty-First Century at 4635 North Market Street -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnce a thriving metropolis on the banks of the Mississippi, St. Louis, Missouri, is now a ghostly landscape of vacant houses, boarded-up storefronts, and abandoned factories. The Gateway City is, by any measure, one of the most depopulated, deindustrialized, and deeply segregated examples of American urban decay. "Not a typical city," as one observer noted in the late 1970s, "but, like a Eugene O'Neill play, it shows a general condition in a stark and dramatic form."Mapping Decline examines the causes and consequences of St. Louis's urban crisis. It traces the complicity of private real estate restrictions, local planning and zoning, and federal housing policies in the "white flight" of people and wealth from the central city. And it traces the inadequacy—and often sheer folly—of a generation of urban renewal, in which even programs and resources aimed at eradicating blight in the city ended up encouraging flight to the suburbs. The urban crisis, as this study of St. Louis makes clear, is not just a consequence of economic and demographic change; it is also the most profound political failure of our recent history.Mapping Decline is the first history of a modern American city to combine extensive local archival research with the latest geographic information system (GIS) digital mapping techniques. More than 75 full-color maps—rendered from census data, archival sources, case law, and local planning and property records—illustrate, in often stark and dramatic ways, the still-unfolding political history of our neglected cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericanszMissourizSaint LouisxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aInner citieszMissourizSaint LouisxHistoryy20th century. 0aSlumszMissourizSaint Louis. 0aUrban renewalzMissourizSaint Louis. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGeneral.  aSocial Science.  aUrban Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229150640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812291506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812291506/original  a978-3-11-045954